Time Model Statistics

  • DB Time represents total time in user calls
  • DB CPU represents CPU time of foreground processes
  • Total CPU Time represents foreground and background processes
  • Statistics including the word "background" measure background process time, therefore do not contribute to the DB time statistic
  • Ordered by % of DB time in descending order, followed by Statistic Name

  • Note there is often a 1:Many correlation between a single logical object in the Library Cache, and the physical number of memory objects associated with it. Therefore comparing the number of Lib Cache objects (e.g. in v$librarycache), with the number of Lib Cache Memory Objects is invalid.

         EB_POSRCDETAILS.POSRCVAL,
         TR_POSRCDETAILS.POSRCVAL
         ) SUM_TR

         AND TRANSMAIN.TRANSEX = to_number(SUM_TR.TR)

Finding 4: Undersized SGA
Impact is 1.22 active sessions, 18.07% of total activity.
---------------------------------------------------------
The SGA was inadequately sized, causing additional I/O or hard parses.
The value of parameter "sga_target" was "1048576 M" during the analysis
period.

   Recommendation 1: Database Configuration
   Estimated benefit is .16 active sessions, 2.39% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Increase the size of the SGA by setting the parameter "sga_target" to
      1114112 M.

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "User I/O" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is 2.24 active sessions, 33.15% of total activity.


Finding 5: DBMS_LOCK Usage
Impact is .19 active sessions, 2.83% of total activity.
-------------------------------------------------------
Waits for locks obtained by using the "DBMS_LOCK" package were consuming
significant database time.

   Recommendation 1: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is .19 active sessions, 2.83% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate application logic that uses the "DBMS_LOCK" package.
      Consider reducing the time these locks are held by the application or
      consider using a finer granularity of locks.

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "Application" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is 1.6 active sessions, 23.61% of total activity.


Finding 6: Commits and Rollbacks
Impact is .15 active sessions, 2.24% of total activity.
-------------------------------------------------------
Waits on event "log file sync" while performing COMMIT and ROLLBACK operations
were consuming significant database time.

   Recommendation 1: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is .15 active sessions, 2.24% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate application logic for possible reduction in the number of
      COMMIT operations by increasing the size of transactions.
   Rationale
      The application was performing 7344 transactions per minute with an
      average redo size of 4680 bytes per transaction.

   Recommendation 2: Host Configuration
   Estimated benefit is .15 active sessions, 2.24% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate the possibility of improving the performance of I/O to the
      online redo log files.
   Rationale
      The average size of writes to the online redo log files was 14 K and the
      average time per write was 2 milliseconds.
   Rationale
      The total I/O throughput on redo log files was 1.2 M per second for
      reads and 1.1 M per second for writes.
   Rationale
      The redo log I/O throughput was divided as follows: 0% by RMAN and
      recovery, 47% by Log Writer, 0% by Archiver, 0% by Streams AQ and 52% by
      all other activity.

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "Commit" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is .15 active sessions, 2.24% of total activity.
